Vladimir Putin and the Risk of World War III
San Francisco – On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a potential world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had a long meeting on February 4 – the day of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebration and the start of the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
Following the meeting, the two issued a carefully crafted 5,000-word document declaring the establishment of a close partnership between their two countries.
This document is more powerful than any treaty and certainly required meticulous negotiations in advance.
I am struck by how Xi seems to have fully entrusted Putin with launching the invasion of Ukraine.
He believes that his confirmation as the lifetime ruler of China later this year will be nothing but a formality, and he is confident about it.
With all power in his hands, Xi carefully crafted a plan to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi’s backing, Putin has set about realizing his lifelong dream with a ferocity almost beyond belief.
At 70, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, either now or never.
But his perception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar to blindly follow.
This system is in stark contrast to democratic societies, and this vision distorts the "soul" of emotionally and sentimentally battered Russian people.
In my childhood, I had many interactions with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they would share their last slice of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I began what I called my political philanthropy.
Initially, I established a foundation in my home country, Hungary, and then became actively involved in efforts to bring down the Soviet Empire.
The breakup had already begun when Mikhail Gorbachev took office in 1985.
I also established foundations in Russia, and subsequently in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I founded a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation there (I closed the foundation in 1989 shortly before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't personally know Putin, but I have been closely following his rise and fully understand his cold-blooded character.
He reduced the Chechen capital Grozny to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, Ukraine's capital.
Putin was a shrewd KGB officer, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed idea.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that Ukrainian speakers would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but it turned out they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking populace.
Despite the seemingly one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian people still engaged in unbelievable brave resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy article claiming that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that the Ukrainians were misled by neo-Nazis.
Since Kyiv was the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, his argument's first part is not without historical basis.
But in the content of the second part, those misled were Putin.
He should have known the facts much better.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely in the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The events of 2014 made him very angry.
But when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
Corruption entrenched in defense contracts played a significant role in this poor performance as well.
But instead of blaming himself, Putin seemed to have gone mad.
He was determined to punish Ukraine in retaliation, and his actions seem to be unbridled.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and disregarded all combat rules, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear plant (now occupied by Russian troops) was destroyed as well.
In Mariupol, which has been under siege, up to 400,000 people have gone without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The US and EU are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine while trying to purchase Russian-made MiG fighters that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
This could change the whole situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has already achieved a miracle in reinforcing Europe's resolve and unity.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has strayed.
<s>On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remained "firm as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, supporting their peace efforts.
<s>To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to maintain maximum restraint in the war.
Whether Putin will comply with Xi's wishes remains doubtful.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
